An evening to forget for Hayne Jarryd Hayne fumbles in one of two touches for the 49ers. San Francisco snapped a four game losing streak with a 5-point win over Baltimore.
PT1M25S 620 349 ï»¿ Live NFL: San Francisco 49ers vs Seattle Seahawks Jarryd Hayne looks to have paid the price for a string of errors after he was left out of the San Francisco 49ers side to face the Seattle Seahawks on Friday morning.
The former Parramatta Eel would have been desperate to get a crack at Pete Carroll's Seahawks, but will have to watch from the sidelines as his fledgling NFL career hits some early but predictable turbulence.
Sitting this one out: Jarryd Hayne. Photo: Getty Images
Coach Jim Tomsula has gone with Bruce Ellington as the first-choice punt returner while Carlos Hyde and Reggie Bush will be used as running backs.
Advertisement It's the first time this season Hayne hasn't been in uniform, but he has endured a few issues with his ball security, fumbling in last week's 25-20 victory over the Baltimore Ravens.
He has averaged 9.5 yards on eight punt returns in his rookie season, while Ellington - the man who replaces Hayne - produced 8.2 yards per return in his rookie season.
Hayne was out and about in the pre-game but won't be involved as the pressure slowly begins to build on his hugely hyped NRL career.
High-profile Sports Illustrated columnist Peter King has already called for the experiment to come to an end.
"Well, the Jarryd Hayne story was fun while it lasted," King wrote. "For the second time in the first six weeks of the season, Hayne fumbled a punt, and the 49ers are not good enough to hand away potential possessions once every three games because they like the former rugby league player's potential.
"It'll be interesting to see how coach Jim Tomsula handles the punt-return job going forward."
As it turns out, Tomsula handled it by putting Hayne on ice.
